{"_id": "29479499|None", "id": "29479499", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "PeerJ. 2018 Feb 19;6:e4391. doi: 10.7717/peerj.4391. eCollection 2018.", "year": "2018", "article-id_pmc": "PMC5822839", "type": "title", "authors": "Iyer S, Acharya KR, Subramanian V"}, "offset": 0, "text": "A comparative bioinformatic analysis of C9orf72.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "203228", "type": "Gene", "ncbi_homologene": "10137", "valid": true, "normalized": [203228], "database": "ncbi_gene", "normalized_id": 203228, "biotype": "gene", "name": "C9orf72", "accession": "@GENE_C9ORF72"}, "text": "C9orf72", "locations": [{"offset": 40, "length": 7}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract"}, "offset": 49, "text": "C9orf72 is associated with frontotemporal dementia (FTD) and Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS), both of which are devastating neurodegenerative diseases. Findings suggest that an expanded hexanucleotide repeat in the non-coding region of the C9orf72 gene is the most common cause of familial FTD and ALS. Despite considerable efforts being made towards discerning the possible disease-causing mechanism/s of this repeat expansion mutation, the biological function of C9orf72 remains unclear. Here, we present the first comprehensive genomic study on C9orf72 gene. Analysis of the genomic level organization of C9orf72 across select species revealed architectural similarity of syntenic regions between human and mouse but a lack of conservation of the repeat-harboring intron 1 sequence. Information generated in this study provides a broad genomic perspective of C9orf72 which would form a basis for subsequent experimental approaches and facilitate future mechanistic and functional studies on this gene.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "203228", "type": "Gene", "ncbi_homologene": "10137", "valid": true, "normalized": [203228], "database": "ncbi_gene", "normalized_id": 203228, 